{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sint Maarten", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Sint Maarten}}\n{{distinguish|2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Saint Martin}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sint Maarten\n| map1 = Sint Maarten-CIA WFB Map.png\n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Sint Maarten]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 17 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=17|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| recovery_cases = 22\n| deaths = 12\n| confirmed_cases = 73<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Chair-of-the-EOC-Silveria-Jacobs%E2%80%AFUpdates-on-COVID19-Developments-for-April-23-2020.aspx|title=Prime Minister & Chair of the EOC Silveria Jacobs\u202fUpdates on COVID-19 Developments for April 23, 2020 |website=Government of Sint Maarten|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><!--<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.facebook.com/SXMGOV/|title=Government of Sint Maarten Coronavirus disease Update April 22nd 2020 |website=Government of Sint Maarten via Facebook|access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref>--> (2020-04-24)\n| suspected_cases =\n| total_ili = \n| website = [http://www.sintmaartengov.org sintmaartengov.org]\n}}\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] in Sint Maarten''' is part of the ongoing global [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|viral pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), which was confirmed to have reached the [[Dutch Caribbean]] island of [[Sint Maarten]] on 17 March 2020. The island is split in a Dutch and French part, with the main airport on the Dutch side and the major harbour on the French side. The first positive test was a French couple from Saint Martin who returned from [[France]] via [[collectivity of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] on 1 March 2020. They were screened and tested positive on the airport, but are counted on the French count.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.smn-news.com/st-maarten-st-martin-news/34052-state-of-affairs-on-st-maarten-regarding-the-covid-19.html |title=St. Martin News Network \u2013 State of Affairs on St. Maarten regarding the COVID-19. |website=smn-news.com|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |date= |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom |url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |date= |website=wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{Medical cases chart\n|numwidth=wmtw <!-- +death coloumn -->\n\n|disease=COVID-19\n|location=Sint Maarten\n|outbreak=2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic\n\n|togglesbar=\n<div class=\"nomobile\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|mar}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|apr}}\n<span class=\"mw-collapsible mw-customtoggle-l15 mw-customtoggle-mar-l15 mw-customtoggle-apr-l15 mw-collapsed\" id=\"mw-customcollapsible-l15\" style=\"padding:0 8px\">Last 15 days</span>\n<span class=\"mw-collapsible mw-customtoggle-l15 mw-customtoggle-mar-l15 mw-customtoggle-apr-l15\" id=\"mw-customcollapsible-l15\" style=\"border:2px solid lightblue; padding:0 8px\">Last 15 days</span>\n</div>\n\n|right2=# of deaths\n|collapsible=y\n|data=\n<!--date;deaths;recoveries;total_cases;;;total_cases;+%;-->\n2020-03-17;  0;  0;  1;;;  1;firstright1=y\n;            0;   ;  1;;;  1;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-22;  0;  0;  2;;;  2;+100%\n2020-03-23;  0;  0;  2;;;  2;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-25;  0;  0;  3;;;  3;+50%\n;            0;  0;  3;;;  3;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-28;  0;  0;  6;;;  6;+100%\n;            0;  0;  6;;;  6;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-31;  1;  0; 16;;; 16;+167%  ;  1;firstright2=y\n2020-04-01;  1;  0; 18;;; 18;+13%   ;  1;=\n2020-04-02;  2;  1; 19;;; 19;+5.6%  ;  2;+100%\n2020-04-03;  4;  1; 23;;; 23;+21%   ;  4;+100%\n2020-04-04;  4;  1; 25;;; 25;+8.7%  ;  4;=\n2020-04-05;  6;  1; 37;;; 37;+48%   ;  6;+50%\n2020-04-06;  6;  1; 40;;; 40;+8.1%  ;  6;=\n2020-04-07;  8;  1; 40;;; 40;=      ;  8;+33%\n2020-04-08;  8;  3; 43;;; 43;+7.5%  ;  8;=\n2020-04-09;  8;  3; 50;;; 50;+16%   ;  8;=\n2020-04-10;  9;  5; 50;;; 50;=      ;  9;+13%\n2020-04-11;  9;  5; 50;;; 50;=      ;  9;=\n2020-04-12;  9;  5; 52;;; 52;+4%    ;  9;=\n2020-04-13;  9;  5; 52;;; 52;=      ;  9;=\n2020-04-14;  9;  5; 53;;; 53;+1.9%  ;  9;=\n2020-04-15;  9; 12; 57;;; 57;+7.6%  ;  9;=\n2020-04-16;  9; 12; 63;;; 63;+11%   ;  9;=\n2020-04-17;  9; 12; 64;;; 64;+1.6%  ;  9;=\n2020-04-18; 10; 12; 67;;; 67;+4.7%  ; 10;+11%\n2020-04-19; 10; 12; 67;;; 67;=      ; 10;=\n2020-04-20; 10; 12; 68;;; 68;+1.5%  ; 10;=\n2020-04-21; 11; 22; 71;;; 71;+4.4%  ; 11;+10%\n2020-04-22; 12; 22; 73;;; 73;+2.8%  ; 12;+9%\n;           12; 22; 73;;; 73;collapsed=y;id=apr\n2020-04-24; 12; 22; 73;;; 73;=      ; 12;=\n|caption=Data sourced from [https://www.facebook.com/SXMGOV/ Facebook page Sint Maarten Government].\n}}\n===March===\nTravel restrictions which were issued by the Government of [[Sint Maarten]] were increased from 14 to 21 days as ordered by Prime Minister [[Silveria Jacobs]] on 11 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-maarten-extends-coronavirus-restrictions-from-14-to-21-days/|title=St. Maarten extends coronavirus restrictions from 14 to 21 days|date=12 March 2020|work=St. Lucia News Online|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Sunday, 22 March 2020 at 11:59&nbsp;pm was the last day for residents (passengers) of St. Maarten to travel back to St. Maarten. After 22 March 2020 the only flights coming into PJIAE airport would be cargo flights or flights that are coming in to pick up passengers to return them to their home address.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/government/VSA/Health-Updates/NOVELCORONAVIRUS/Pages/Travel-advice.aspx |title= Government of St Maarten COVID-19 Travel Restrictions|work= Government of St Maarten|access-date= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nA decision was made on 12 March 2020 to postpone Carnival 2020 after emergency meetings were held with the Emergency Operations Center (EOC) and Members of Parliament. The decision to postpone Carnival was taken in keeping with the WHO recommendations which advises persons to avoid large crowds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Jacobs-postpones-Carnival-2020-until-further-notice.aspx |title= Prime Minister Jacobs postpones Carnival 2020 until further notice | work=Government of St Maarten |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2020 the first positive case in Sint Maarten was confirmed. A local male resident who had recently traveled to the United Kingdom (UK) via Miami was registered as the country's first Coronavirus COVID-19 case on Tuesday, 17 March 2020 by the Prime Minister and EOC chair-person Silveria Jacobs.<ref name=\"WOMC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus Update (Live) \u2013 Worldometer |website=worldometers.info}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Address-on-COVID19-MARCH-17-2020.aspx |title=National Address by Prime Minister Silveria E. Jacobs |work= Government of St Maarten |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> To further mitigate the spread of COVID-19 all schools and non-essential businesses were shut down for 14 days On 18 March 2020 at 12:00&nbsp;am.<ref name=\"national_address\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Address-on-COVID19-MARCH-17-2020.aspx |title=National Address by Prime Minister Silveria E. Jacobs |work= Government of St Maarten |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 22 March 2020, there were 2 confirmed cases on St Maarten.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Address-on-COVID-19-MARCH-22-2020.aspx |title= Prime Minister Silveria Jacobs National Address on COVID-19 MARCH 22, 2020 |work= Government of St Maarten|access-date= 4 April 2020}}</ref> The second case is a student who had returned from abroad. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/returning-student-is-dutch-side-s-second-covid-19-case|title=Returning student is Dutch side\u2019s second COVID-19 case |website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, Prime Minister Silveria Jacobs announced that the number of coronavirus COVID-19 cases had risen to 6, of which 2 were hospitalized.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Chair-of-the-EOC-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Address-on-COVID19-Developments-MARCH-28-2020.aspx |title= Prime Minister & Chair of the EOC Silveria Jacobs National Address on COVID-19 Developments MARCH 28, 2020 |work= Government of St Maarten |access-date= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 2020 a decision was made by the Government of St Maarten to increase further restrictions on the movement of persons throughout the island via a Ministerial Regulation. This regulation requires citizens to carry a document on them, signed by their employer, declaring the need for them to travel to work (Form A), or one which describes which essential service they are traveling to or for (Form B). On 30 March 2020 a curfew from 8:00&nbsp;pm to 6:00&nbsp;am was implemented for the remainder of the COVID-19 period.<ref name=\"travel_restriction\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Chair-of-the-EOC-Silveria-Jacobs-Updates-on-COVID19-Developments-MARCH-29-2020.aspx |title= Prime Minister & Chair of the EOC Silveria Jacobs Updates on COVID-19 Developments MARCH 29, 2020 |work= Government of St Maarten}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2020 a further 10 positive cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of cases to 16. St Maarten recorded its first death from the disease that same day. The person was at the time of death a suspected case in isolation at home. In total, 58 persons were tested with 16 testing positive, and 36 testing negative.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Chair-of-the-EOC-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Briefing-on-COVID19-Developments-MARCH-31-2020.aspx |title=Prime Minister & Chair of the EOC Silveria Jacobs National Briefing on COVID-19 Developments MARCH 31, 2020 |work= Government of St Maarten}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n[[File:Medische zending naar Sint Maarten (Covid-19).jpg|thumb|Medical shipment to Sint Maarten]]\nOn 2 April 2020 the total numbers of COVID-19 cases rose to 23, of which 18 were male, 5 were female. 3 cases were currently hospitalized, and 1 new death was recorded bringing the total number of deaths to two. The additional death listed succumbed at St. Maarten Medical Center (SMMC) on Thursday, 2 April.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Chair-of-the-EOC-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Address-on-COVID19-Developments-APRIL-2-2020.aspx |title= National Address on COVID19 Developments APRIL 2 2020 |work= Government of St Maarten}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/government/VSA/Health-Updates/NOVELCORONAVIRUS/Pages/Current-Situation.aspx |title=Current Situation on Sint Maarten |work= Government of St Maarten}}</ref>\n<br>\nHealth Care Laboratory Sint Maarten and the laboratory in Cole Bay now have the ability to test for Covid-19, but they only have a limited amount of kits,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/local-lab-can-test-for-virus-but-not-many-kits-available|title=Local lab can test for virus, but not many kits available|website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> therefore tests of people without symptoms are often forwarded to [[Guadelope]] which will take 3 to 5 days.<ref name=\"ntr_eustatius\">{{Cite news|url=https://caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl/2020/04/02/sint-eustatius-aangeslagen-door-eerste-coronabesmettingen/ |title=Sint-Eustatius aangeslagen door eerste coronabesmettingen |language=nl|access-date=20 April 2020 |website=Caribisch Netwerk NTR }}</ref>\n\nOn Friday, 3 April 2020 the number of deaths climbed to four when two more persons died. Between 31 March 2020 and 3 April 2020 four persons have succumbed to the illness in four days. Collective Prevention Services (CPS) head epidemiologist Eva Lista-de Weever, who confirmed the two additional deaths, said the total number of confirmed cases still stands at 23 as of 3 April 2020. Prime Minister and Emergency Operations Center (EOC) Chairperson Silveria Jacobs said a total shutdown is being planned due to the trend of increasing COVID-19 fatalities. A National Decree regarding the curfew has been prepared and was sent to Governor Eugene Holiday. The date of the total shutdown is awaiting confirmation of the decree.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/update-2-more-covid-19-deaths-on-dutch-side-total-shutdown-being-planned |title=2 more COVID-19 deaths on Dutch side, total shutdown being planned |work= The Daily Herald Sxm |access-date= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2020, a total lock-down went into effect. Nobody is allowed to leave their house for the coming two weeks. <ref name=\"total_lockdown\">{{Cite news|url=https://caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl/2020/04/05/sint-maarten-op-totale-lockdown-medische-hulpgoederen-onderweg/ |title=Sint-Maarten op totale lockdown: Medische hulpgoederen onderweg |language=nl |website=Caribisch Netwerk [[Omroep NTR|NTR]]| access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> The lock-down which was announced on 4 April, caused long queues at the supermarket. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/state-of-emergency-called-two-week-shutdown-to-start-midnight-tonight|title=State of emergency called, two-week shutdown to start midnight tonight|access-date=21 April 2020|website=The Daily Herald.sx}}</ref>. It was later announced that supermarkets are allowed to deliver. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl/2020/04/07/supermarkten-op-sint-maarten-mogen-tijdens-lockdown-bezorgen/ |title=Supermarkten op Sint-Maarten mogen tijdens lockdown bezorgen |access-date=21 April 2020|language=nl|website=Caribisch Network NTR}}</ref>\n<br>\nRespirators, medical supplies, and six [[intensive care|ICU]] beds were flown to Sint Maarten by the Dutch government. Sint Maarten was considered the hardest hit island and therefore received the supplies five days before the other islands. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.culturu.com/nieuws/nederland/medische-spullen-uit-nederland-naar-st-maarten/ |title=Medische spullen uit Nederland naar St. Maarten |language=nl |website=Culturu.com |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 2020, the government came under scrutiny. Melissa Gumbs and Raeyhon Peterson of Party For Progress criticised the haphazard announcement one day before the total lock-down came into effect, and the exclusion of Parliament in this decision. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/pfp-questions-jacobs-on-abrupt-nature-of-total-lockdown |title=PFP questions Jacobs on \u2018abrupt nature\u2019 of total lockdown |website=The Daily Herald.sx |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n<br>\nThe minor roads were physically blocked to prevent border crossings. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/barricaded|title=Barricaded |website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 2020, it was announced that the ladies at the regulated [[brothel]] \"Campo Alegre\" were allowed to be repatriated, however many feared losing their $500,- deposit. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/sex-workers-could-go-home-on-saturday |title=Sex workers could go home on Saturday |access-date=21 April 2020|website=The Daily Herald.sx}}</ref>\n\nAs a 15 April 2020, there were 91 people in self-quarantine and 161 in self-isolation. 161 people were tested of which 53 tested positive (35 males and 18 females). Nine people have died and five have recovered.<ref>http://www.sintmaartengov.org/government/VSA/Health-Updates/NOVELCORONAVIRUS/Pages/Current-Situation.aspx</ref>\n\nOn 16 April 2020, Egbert Doran, Minister of Public Housing, Spatial Planning, Environment and Infrastructure, asked all the flags to be flown half-mast and observe a day of mourning. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/st-maarten-in-period-of-mourning-flags-at-half-mast-at-govt-offices|title=St. Maarten in period of mourning, flags at half-mast at govt. offices|website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April 2020, the total lock-down was ended causing long lines at the supermarkets. <ref name=\"supermarkets_reopened\">{{Cite news|url=https://caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl/2020/04/17/lange-rijen-voor-supermarkten-heel-blij-met-deze-kans/ |title=Lange rijen voor supermarkten: \u2018Heel blij met deze kans\u2019 |website=Caribisch Netwerk NTR| access-date=21 April 2020| language=nl}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April 2020, Prime Minister [[Silveria Jacobs]] announced that the tenth and most recent death was a Dutch citizen who was being treated on the French side. Last week he was flown to [[Guadelope]] for critical care, however as Dutch citizen he will be removed from the French Saint Martin count and added to the Dutch Sint Maarten count. <ref name=\"tenth_death\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/three-more-positive-cases-1-more-covid-19-death-for-st-maarten|title=Three more positive cases, 1 more COVID-19 death for St. Maarten|website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April 2020, Prime Minister Jacobs announced that nine people had been found with flu-like symptoms, but that only six consented to be tested. These are the preliminary figures of the Ministry of Health going door to door to find suspected cases.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/cps-visits-242-households-six-of-nine-with-symptoms-consented-to-be-tested|title=CPS visits 242 households, six of nine with symptoms consented to be tested |access-date=21 April 2020|website=The Daily Herald.sx}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 April 2020, Jacobs announced that there were three health care workerss among the recent updates. There were no new cases reported on 23 April, because the test results were still pending. 900 additional test kits had been received.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/three-healthcare-workers-among-those-tested-positive-for-covid-19|title=Three healthcare workers among those tested positive for COVID-19|website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n<br>\nThe [[HNLMS Karel Doorman (A833)|''Zr. Ms. Karel Doorman'']] which was dispatched from [[Den Helder]] on 13 April to assist with food aid, border control and public order,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobonaire.com/navy-ship-zr-ms-karel-doorman-to-the-caribbean/|title=Navy ship Zr Ms Karel Doorman to the Caribbean|access-date=17 April 2020|website=The Bonaire Information Site|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415075252/https://www.infobonaire.com/navy-ship-zr-ms-karel-doorman-to-the-caribbean/|archive-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> has arrived in Sint Maarten. The Netherlands, [[France]] and [[United Kingdom]] will jointly patrol the waters of the Caribbean.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/navy-ship-arrives-to-help-in-corona-crisis|title=Navy ship arrives to help in corona crisis |access-date=25 April 2020|website=The Daily Herald.sx}}</ref>\n\n==Preventive measures==\nOn 17 March, the airport and ports are closed for passengers. This does not apply to residents of Sint Maarten who have to quarantine for 14 days, and essential travel from [[Saba]], [[Sint-Eustatius]], and [[Cura\u00e7ao]].<ref name=\"national_address\"/> All school are closed.<ref name=\"national_address\"/>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, a list of maximum prices for some essential goods was published. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/government/VSA/Health-Updates/NOVELCORONAVIRUS/Documents/Bijlage%20behorende%20bij%20de%20Regeling%20prijsvaststelling%20in%20verband%20met%20de%20coronavirus%20(COVID-19).pdf |title=Maximum Price Regulation (PDF)| access-date=21 April 2020|website=The Government of Sint Maarten}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.curacaochronicle.com/post/main/maximum-price-for-vegetables-and-fruit-in-curacao/|title=Maximum price for vegetables and fruit in Cura\u00e7ao|website=Cura\u00e7ao Chronicle|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, everybody should stay at home except when they have a special permission to travel.<ref name=\"travel_restriction\"/> The border between Sint Maarten and Saint Martin is closed and jointly patrolled with the French government. <ref name=\"travel_restriction\"/> Restaurants are take-away only and are not allowed to sell alcoholic beverages. <ref name=\"travel_restriction\"/> The alcohol ban was lifted on 15 April. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/suspension-on-alcohol-sales-lifted-from-today|title=Suspension on alcohol sales lifted from today |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, a curfew was implemented from 20:00 until 6:00. <ref name=\"travel_restriction\"/>\n\nOn 5 April 2020, a total lock-down was announced. Nobody is allowed to leave their house for the coming two weeks. <ref name=\"total_lockdown\"/> The lock-down ended on 17 April 2020. <ref name=\"supermarkets_reopened\"/>\n\nOn 21 April 2020, certain shops are allowed to open for delivery and the beaches are open between 06:00 and 09:00. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://unitednews.sr/weer-versoepeling-van-de-lockdown-regels-op-curacao/|title=WEER VERSOEPELING VAN DE LOCKDOWN REGELS OP CURA\u00c7AO|language=nl|access-date=21 April 2020|website=Dagblad Suriname}}</ref> The post office reopened for three days a week in the morning. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/post-office-now-open-three-days-a-week|title=Post Office now open three days a week |website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"> </div>\n==Statistics==\nChronology of the number of active cases\n{{Graph:Chart\n| type = line\n| linewidth = 1\n| showSymbols = 1\n| yType= integer\n| width = 600\n| colors = #ff6347, cyan, black\n| xAxisTitle = Date\n| xAxisAngle = -40\n| xType = date\n| xAxisFormat = %e %b\n| x = 16 March 2020, 17 March 2020, 18 March 2020, 19 March 2020, 20 March 2020, 21 March 2020, 22 March 2020, 23 March 2020, 24 March 2020, 25 March 2020, 26 March 2020, 27 March 2020, 28 March 2020, 29 March 2020, 30 March 2020, 31 March 2020,\n1 April 2020, 2 April 2020, 3 April 2020, 4 April 2020, 5 April 2020, 6 April 2020, 7 April 2020, 8 April 2020, 9 April 2020, 10 April 2020, 11 April 2020, 12 April 2020, 13 April 2020, 14 April 2020, 15 April 2020, 16 April 2020, 17 April 2020, 18 April 2020, 19 April 2020, 20 April 2020, 21 April 2020, 22 April 2020, 23 April 2020, 24 April 2020\n| yAxisTitle = No. of cases\n| y1 = \n0,   1,  1,  1,  1,  1,  2,  2,  2,  3,  3,  3,  6,  6,  6, 15,  <!--     March -->\n17, 20, 18, 20, 30, 33, 31, 32, 39, 36, 36, 38, 38, 39, 36,  <!-- -15 April -->\n42, 43, 45, 45, 46, 38, 39, 39, 39\n| yGrid = \n| xGrid = \n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Saint Martin]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saba]]\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sintmaartengov.org/Pages/default.aspx Official Website of the Government of Sint Maarten]\n* [https://www.consulytic.com/corona Dashboard Caribbean]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{#related:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Saint Martin}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saba}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Sint Maarten]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Dutch Caribbean|Sint Maarten]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Sint Maarten]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Sint Maarten}}\n{{distinguish|2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Saint Martin}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sint Maarten\n| map1 = Sint Maarten-CIA WFB Map.png\n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Sint Maarten]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 17 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=17|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| recovery_cases = 22\n| deaths = 12\n| confirmed_cases = 73<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Chair-of-the-EOC-Silveria-Jacobs%E2%80%AFUpdates-on-COVID19-Developments-for-April-23-2020.aspx|title=Prime Minister & Chair of the EOC Silveria Jacobs\u202fUpdates on COVID-19 Developments for April 23, 2020 |website=Government of Sint Maarten|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><!--<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.facebook.com/SXMGOV/|title=Government of Sint Maarten Coronavirus disease Update April 22nd 2020 |website=Government of Sint Maarten via Facebook|access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref>--> (2020-04-24)\n| suspected_cases =\n| total_ili = \n| website = [http://www.sintmaartengov.org sintmaartengov.org]\n}}\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] in Sint Maarten''' is part of the ongoing global [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|viral pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), which was confirmed to have reached the [[Dutch Caribbean]] island of [[Sint Maarten]] on 17 March 2020. The island is split in a Dutch and French part, with the main airport on the Dutch side and the major harbour on the French side. The first positive test was a French couple from Saint Martin who returned from [[France]] via [[collectivity of Saint Barth\u00e9lemy|Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]] on 1 March 2020. They were screened and tested positive on the airport, but are counted on the French count.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.smn-news.com/st-maarten-st-martin-news/34052-state-of-affairs-on-st-maarten-regarding-the-covid-19.html |title=St. Martin News Network \u2013 State of Affairs on St. Maarten regarding the COVID-19. |website=smn-news.com|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |date= |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom |url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |date= |website=wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{Medical cases chart\n|numwidth=wmtw <!-- +death coloumn -->\n\n|disease=COVID-19\n|location=Sint Maarten\n|outbreak=2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic\n\n|togglesbar=\n<div class=\"nomobile\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|mar}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|apr}}\n<span class=\"mw-collapsible mw-customtoggle-l15 mw-customtoggle-mar-l15 mw-customtoggle-apr-l15 mw-collapsed\" id=\"mw-customcollapsible-l15\" style=\"padding:0 8px\">Last 15 days</span>\n<span class=\"mw-collapsible mw-customtoggle-l15 mw-customtoggle-mar-l15 mw-customtoggle-apr-l15\" id=\"mw-customcollapsible-l15\" style=\"border:2px solid lightblue; padding:0 8px\">Last 15 days</span>\n</div>\n\n|right2=# of deaths\n|collapsible=y\n|data=\n<!--date;deaths;recoveries;total_cases;;;total_cases;+%;-->\n2020-03-17;  0;  0;  1;;;  1;firstright1=y\n;            0;   ;  1;;;  1;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-22;  0;  0;  2;;;  2;+100%\n2020-03-23;  0;  0;  2;;;  2;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-25;  0;  0;  3;;;  3;+50%\n;            0;  0;  3;;;  3;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-28;  0;  0;  6;;;  6;+100%\n;            0;  0;  6;;;  6;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-31;  1;  0; 16;;; 16;+167%  ;  1;firstright2=y\n2020-04-01;  1;  0; 18;;; 18;+13%   ;  1;=\n2020-04-02;  2;  1; 19;;; 19;+5.6%  ;  2;+100%\n2020-04-03;  4;  1; 23;;; 23;+21%   ;  4;+100%\n2020-04-04;  4;  1; 25;;; 25;+8.7%  ;  4;=\n2020-04-05;  6;  1; 37;;; 37;+48%   ;  6;+50%\n2020-04-06;  6;  1; 40;;; 40;+8.1%  ;  6;=\n2020-04-07;  8;  1; 40;;; 40;=      ;  8;+33%\n2020-04-08;  8;  3; 43;;; 43;+7.5%  ;  8;=\n2020-04-09;  8;  3; 50;;; 50;+16%   ;  8;=\n2020-04-10;  9;  5; 50;;; 50;=      ;  9;+13%\n2020-04-11;  9;  5; 50;;; 50;=      ;  9;=\n2020-04-12;  9;  5; 52;;; 52;+4%    ;  9;=\n2020-04-13;  9;  5; 52;;; 52;=      ;  9;=\n2020-04-14;  9;  5; 53;;; 53;+1.9%  ;  9;=\n2020-04-15;  9; 12; 57;;; 57;+7.6%  ;  9;=\n2020-04-16;  9; 12; 63;;; 63;+11%   ;  9;=\n2020-04-17;  9; 12; 64;;; 64;+1.6%  ;  9;=\n2020-04-18; 10; 12; 67;;; 67;+4.7%  ; 10;+11%\n2020-04-19; 10; 12; 67;;; 67;=      ; 10;=\n2020-04-20; 10; 12; 68;;; 68;+1.5%  ; 10;=\n2020-04-21; 11; 22; 71;;; 71;+4.4%  ; 11;+10%\n2020-04-22; 12; 22; 73;;; 73;+2.8%  ; 12;+9%\n;           12; 22; 73;;;  6;collapsed=y;id=apr\n|caption=Data sourced from [https://www.facebook.com/SXMGOV/ Facebook page Sint Maarten Government].\n}}\n===March===\nTravel restrictions which were issued by the Government of [[Sint Maarten]] were increased from 14 to 21 days as ordered by Prime Minister [[Silveria Jacobs]] on 11 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-maarten-extends-coronavirus-restrictions-from-14-to-21-days/|title=St. Maarten extends coronavirus restrictions from 14 to 21 days|date=12 March 2020|work=St. Lucia News Online|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Sunday, 22 March 2020 at 11:59&nbsp;pm was the last day for residents (passengers) of St. Maarten to travel back to St. Maarten. After 22 March 2020 the only flights coming into PJIAE airport would be cargo flights or flights that are coming in to pick up passengers to return them to their home address.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/government/VSA/Health-Updates/NOVELCORONAVIRUS/Pages/Travel-advice.aspx |title= Government of St Maarten COVID-19 Travel Restrictions|work= Government of St Maarten|access-date= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nA decision was made on 12 March 2020 to postpone Carnival 2020 after emergency meetings were held with the Emergency Operations Center (EOC) and Members of Parliament. The decision to postpone Carnival was taken in keeping with the WHO recommendations which advises persons to avoid large crowds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Jacobs-postpones-Carnival-2020-until-further-notice.aspx |title= Prime Minister Jacobs postpones Carnival 2020 until further notice | work=Government of St Maarten |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2020 the first positive case in Sint Maarten was confirmed. A local male resident who had recently traveled to the United Kingdom (UK) via Miami was registered as the country's first Coronavirus COVID-19 case on Tuesday, 17 March 2020 by the Prime Minister and EOC chair-person Silveria Jacobs.<ref name=\"WOMC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus Update (Live) \u2013 Worldometer |website=worldometers.info}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Address-on-COVID19-MARCH-17-2020.aspx |title=National Address by Prime Minister Silveria E. Jacobs |work= Government of St Maarten |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref> To further mitigate the spread of COVID-19 all schools and non-essential businesses were shut down for 14 days On 18 March 2020 at 12:00&nbsp;am.<ref name=\"national_address\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Address-on-COVID19-MARCH-17-2020.aspx |title=National Address by Prime Minister Silveria E. Jacobs |work= Government of St Maarten |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of 22 March 2020, there were 2 confirmed cases on St Maarten.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Address-on-COVID-19-MARCH-22-2020.aspx |title= Prime Minister Silveria Jacobs National Address on COVID-19 MARCH 22, 2020 |work= Government of St Maarten|access-date= 4 April 2020}}</ref> The second case is a student who had returned from abroad. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/returning-student-is-dutch-side-s-second-covid-19-case|title=Returning student is Dutch side\u2019s second COVID-19 case |website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2020, Prime Minister Silveria Jacobs announced that the number of coronavirus COVID-19 cases had risen to 6, of which 2 were hospitalized.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Chair-of-the-EOC-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Address-on-COVID19-Developments-MARCH-28-2020.aspx |title= Prime Minister & Chair of the EOC Silveria Jacobs National Address on COVID-19 Developments MARCH 28, 2020 |work= Government of St Maarten |access-date= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 2020 a decision was made by the Government of St Maarten to increase further restrictions on the movement of persons throughout the island via a Ministerial Regulation. This regulation requires citizens to carry a document on them, signed by their employer, declaring the need for them to travel to work (Form A), or one which describes which essential service they are traveling to or for (Form B). On 30 March 2020 a curfew from 8:00&nbsp;pm to 6:00&nbsp;am was implemented for the remainder of the COVID-19 period.<ref name=\"travel_restriction\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Chair-of-the-EOC-Silveria-Jacobs-Updates-on-COVID19-Developments-MARCH-29-2020.aspx |title= Prime Minister & Chair of the EOC Silveria Jacobs Updates on COVID-19 Developments MARCH 29, 2020 |work= Government of St Maarten}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2020 a further 10 positive cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of cases to 16. St Maarten recorded its first death from the disease that same day. The person was at the time of death a suspected case in isolation at home. In total, 58 persons were tested with 16 testing positive, and 36 testing negative.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Chair-of-the-EOC-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Briefing-on-COVID19-Developments-MARCH-31-2020.aspx |title=Prime Minister & Chair of the EOC Silveria Jacobs National Briefing on COVID-19 Developments MARCH 31, 2020 |work= Government of St Maarten}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n[[File:Medische zending naar Sint Maarten (Covid-19).jpg|thumb|Medical shipment to Sint Maarten]]\nOn 2 April 2020 the total numbers of COVID-19 cases rose to 23, of which 18 were male, 5 were female. 3 cases were currently hospitalized, and 1 new death was recorded bringing the total number of deaths to two. The additional death listed succumbed at St. Maarten Medical Center (SMMC) on Thursday, 2 April.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/PressReleases/Pages/Prime-Minister-Chair-of-the-EOC-Silveria-Jacobs-National-Address-on-COVID19-Developments-APRIL-2-2020.aspx |title= National Address on COVID19 Developments APRIL 2 2020 |work= Government of St Maarten}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/government/VSA/Health-Updates/NOVELCORONAVIRUS/Pages/Current-Situation.aspx |title=Current Situation on Sint Maarten |work= Government of St Maarten}}</ref>\n<br>\nHealth Care Laboratory Sint Maarten and the laboratory in Cole Bay now have the ability to test for Covid-19, but they only have a limited amount of kits,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/local-lab-can-test-for-virus-but-not-many-kits-available|title=Local lab can test for virus, but not many kits available|website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref> therefore tests of people without symptoms are often forwarded to [[Guadelope]] which will take 3 to 5 days.<ref name=\"ntr_eustatius\">{{Cite news|url=https://caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl/2020/04/02/sint-eustatius-aangeslagen-door-eerste-coronabesmettingen/ |title=Sint-Eustatius aangeslagen door eerste coronabesmettingen |language=nl|access-date=20 April 2020 |website=Caribisch Netwerk NTR }}</ref>\n\nOn Friday, 3 April 2020 the number of deaths climbed to four when two more persons died. Between 31 March 2020 and 3 April 2020 four persons have succumbed to the illness in four days. Collective Prevention Services (CPS) head epidemiologist Eva Lista-de Weever, who confirmed the two additional deaths, said the total number of confirmed cases still stands at 23 as of 3 April 2020. Prime Minister and Emergency Operations Center (EOC) Chairperson Silveria Jacobs said a total shutdown is being planned due to the trend of increasing COVID-19 fatalities. A National Decree regarding the curfew has been prepared and was sent to Governor Eugene Holiday. The date of the total shutdown is awaiting confirmation of the decree.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/update-2-more-covid-19-deaths-on-dutch-side-total-shutdown-being-planned |title=2 more COVID-19 deaths on Dutch side, total shutdown being planned |work= The Daily Herald Sxm |access-date= 4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2020, a total lock-down went into effect. Nobody is allowed to leave their house for the coming two weeks. <ref name=\"total_lockdown\">{{Cite news|url=https://caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl/2020/04/05/sint-maarten-op-totale-lockdown-medische-hulpgoederen-onderweg/ |title=Sint-Maarten op totale lockdown: Medische hulpgoederen onderweg |language=nl |website=Caribisch Netwerk [[Omroep NTR|NTR]]| access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> The lock-down which was announced on 4 April, caused long queues at the supermarket. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/state-of-emergency-called-two-week-shutdown-to-start-midnight-tonight|title=State of emergency called, two-week shutdown to start midnight tonight|access-date=21 April 2020|website=The Daily Herald.sx}}</ref>. It was later announced that supermarkets are allowed to deliver. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl/2020/04/07/supermarkten-op-sint-maarten-mogen-tijdens-lockdown-bezorgen/ |title=Supermarkten op Sint-Maarten mogen tijdens lockdown bezorgen |access-date=21 April 2020|language=nl|website=Caribisch Network NTR}}</ref>\n<br>\nRespirators, medical supplies, and six [[intensive care|ICU]] beds were flown to Sint Maarten by the Dutch government. Sint Maarten was considered the hardest hit island and therefore received the supplies five days before the other islands. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.culturu.com/nieuws/nederland/medische-spullen-uit-nederland-naar-st-maarten/ |title=Medische spullen uit Nederland naar St. Maarten |language=nl |website=Culturu.com |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April 2020, the government came under scrutiny. Melissa Gumbs and Raeyhon Peterson of Party For Progress criticised the haphazard announcement one day before the total lock-down came into effect, and the exclusion of Parliament in this decision. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/pfp-questions-jacobs-on-abrupt-nature-of-total-lockdown |title=PFP questions Jacobs on \u2018abrupt nature\u2019 of total lockdown |website=The Daily Herald.sx |access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n<br>\nThe minor roads were physically blocked to prevent border crossings. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/barricaded|title=Barricaded |website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 2020, it was announced that the ladies at the regulated [[brothel]] \"Campo Alegre\" were allowed to be repatriated, however many feared losing their $500,- deposit. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/sex-workers-could-go-home-on-saturday |title=Sex workers could go home on Saturday |access-date=21 April 2020|website=The Daily Herald.sx}}</ref>\n\nAs a 15 April 2020, there were 91 people in self-quarantine and 161 in self-isolation. 161 people were tested of which 53 tested positive (35 males and 18 females). Nine people have died and five have recovered.<ref>http://www.sintmaartengov.org/government/VSA/Health-Updates/NOVELCORONAVIRUS/Pages/Current-Situation.aspx</ref>\n\nOn 16 April 2020, Egbert Doran, Minister of Public Housing, Spatial Planning, Environment and Infrastructure, asked all the flags to be flown half-mast and observe a day of mourning. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/st-maarten-in-period-of-mourning-flags-at-half-mast-at-govt-offices|title=St. Maarten in period of mourning, flags at half-mast at govt. offices|website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April 2020, the total lock-down was ended causing long lines at the supermarkets. <ref name=\"supermarkets_reopened\">{{Cite news|url=https://caribischnetwerk.ntr.nl/2020/04/17/lange-rijen-voor-supermarkten-heel-blij-met-deze-kans/ |title=Lange rijen voor supermarkten: \u2018Heel blij met deze kans\u2019 |website=Caribisch Netwerk NTR| access-date=21 April 2020| language=nl}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 April 2020, Prime Minister [[Silveria Jacobs]] announced that the tenth and most recent death was a Dutch citizen who was being treated on the French side. Last week he was flown to [[Guadelope]] for critical care, however as Dutch citizen he will be removed from the French Saint Martin count and added to the Dutch Sint Maarten count. <ref name=\"tenth_death\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/three-more-positive-cases-1-more-covid-19-death-for-st-maarten|title=Three more positive cases, 1 more COVID-19 death for St. Maarten|website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 April 2020, Prime Minister Jacobs announced that nine people had been found with flu-like symptoms, but that only six consented to be tested. These are the preliminary figures of the Ministry of Health going door to door to find suspected cases.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/cps-visits-242-households-six-of-nine-with-symptoms-consented-to-be-tested|title=CPS visits 242 households, six of nine with symptoms consented to be tested |access-date=21 April 2020|website=The Daily Herald.sx}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 April 2020, Jacobs announced that there were three health care workerss among the recent updates. There were no new cases reported on 23 April, because the test results were still pending. 900 additional test kits had been received.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/three-healthcare-workers-among-those-tested-positive-for-covid-19|title=Three healthcare workers among those tested positive for COVID-19|website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n<br>\nThe [[HNLMS Karel Doorman (A833)|''Zr. Ms. Karel Doorman'']] which was dispatched from [[Den Helder]] on 13 April to assist with food aid, border control and public order,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobonaire.com/navy-ship-zr-ms-karel-doorman-to-the-caribbean/|title=Navy ship Zr Ms Karel Doorman to the Caribbean|access-date=17 April 2020|website=The Bonaire Information Site|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415075252/https://www.infobonaire.com/navy-ship-zr-ms-karel-doorman-to-the-caribbean/|archive-date=15 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> has arrived in Sint Maarten. The Netherlands, [[France]] and [[United Kingdom]] will jointly patrol the waters of the Caribbean.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/navy-ship-arrives-to-help-in-corona-crisis|title=Navy ship arrives to help in corona crisis |access-date=25 April 2020|website=The Daily Herald.sx}}</ref>\n\n==Preventive measures==\nOn 17 March, the airport and ports are closed for passengers. This does not apply to residents of Sint Maarten who have to quarantine for 14 days, and essential travel from [[Saba]], [[Sint-Eustatius]], and [[Cura\u00e7ao]].<ref name=\"national_address\"/> All school are closed.<ref name=\"national_address\"/>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, a list of maximum prices for some essential goods was published. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sintmaartengov.org/government/VSA/Health-Updates/NOVELCORONAVIRUS/Documents/Bijlage%20behorende%20bij%20de%20Regeling%20prijsvaststelling%20in%20verband%20met%20de%20coronavirus%20(COVID-19).pdf |title=Maximum Price Regulation (PDF)| access-date=21 April 2020|website=The Government of Sint Maarten}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.curacaochronicle.com/post/main/maximum-price-for-vegetables-and-fruit-in-curacao/|title=Maximum price for vegetables and fruit in Cura\u00e7ao|website=Cura\u00e7ao Chronicle|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, everybody should stay at home except when they have a special permission to travel.<ref name=\"travel_restriction\"/> The border between Sint Maarten and Saint Martin is closed and jointly patrolled with the French government. <ref name=\"travel_restriction\"/> Restaurants are take-away only and are not allowed to sell alcoholic beverages. <ref name=\"travel_restriction\"/> The alcohol ban was lifted on 15 April. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/suspension-on-alcohol-sales-lifted-from-today|title=Suspension on alcohol sales lifted from today |access-date=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, a curfew was implemented from 20:00 until 6:00. <ref name=\"travel_restriction\"/>\n\nOn 5 April 2020, a total lock-down was announced. Nobody is allowed to leave their house for the coming two weeks. <ref name=\"total_lockdown\"/> The lock-down ended on 17 April 2020. <ref name=\"supermarkets_reopened\"/>\n\nOn 21 April 2020, certain shops are allowed to open for delivery and the beaches are open between 06:00 and 09:00. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://unitednews.sr/weer-versoepeling-van-de-lockdown-regels-op-curacao/|title=WEER VERSOEPELING VAN DE LOCKDOWN REGELS OP CURA\u00c7AO|language=nl|access-date=21 April 2020|website=Dagblad Suriname}}</ref> The post office reopened for three days a week in the morning. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/islands/post-office-now-open-three-days-a-week|title=Post Office now open three days a week |website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"> </div>\n==Statistics==\nChronology of the number of active cases\n{{Graph:Chart\n| type = line\n| linewidth = 1\n| showSymbols = 1\n| yType= integer\n| width = 600\n| colors = #ff6347, cyan, black\n| xAxisTitle = Date\n| xAxisAngle = -40\n| xType = date\n| xAxisFormat = %e %b\n| x = 16 March 2020, 17 March 2020, 18 March 2020, 19 March 2020, 20 March 2020, 21 March 2020, 22 March 2020, 23 March 2020, 24 March 2020, 25 March 2020, 26 March 2020, 27 March 2020, 28 March 2020, 29 March 2020, 30 March 2020, 31 March 2020,\n1 April 2020, 2 April 2020, 3 April 2020, 4 April 2020, 5 April 2020, 6 April 2020, 7 April 2020, 8 April 2020, 9 April 2020, 10 April 2020, 11 April 2020, 12 April 2020, 13 April 2020, 14 April 2020, 15 April 2020, 16 April 2020, 17 April 2020, 18 April 2020, 19 April 2020, 20 April 2020, 21 April 2020, 22 April 2020, 23 April 2020, 24 April 2020\n| yAxisTitle = No. of cases\n| y1 = \n0,   1,  1,  1,  1,  1,  2,  2,  2,  3,  3,  3,  6,  6,  6, 15,  <!--     March -->\n17, 20, 18, 20, 30, 33, 31, 32, 39, 36, 36, 38, 38, 39, 36,  <!-- -15 April -->\n42, 43, 45, 45, 46, 38, 39, 39, 39\n| yGrid = \n| xGrid = \n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Saint Martin]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saba]]\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sintmaartengov.org/Pages/default.aspx Official Website of the Government of Sint Maarten]\n* [https://www.consulytic.com/corona Dashboard Caribbean]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{#related:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in French Saint Martin}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saba}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Sint Maarten]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Dutch Caribbean|Sint Maarten]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Sint Maarten]]\n", "name_user": "KittenKlub", "label": "safe", "comment": "corr", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Sint_Maarten"}
{"title_page": "Yusuf Arakkal", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Refimprove|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Yusuf Arakkal\n| image         = YusufArakkalPic.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Yusuf Arakkal\n| birth_date    = 1945\n| birth_place   = Chavakkad, Thrissur, Kerala<ref name=\"R1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/art-and-culture/artist-yusuf-arakkal-passes-away-at-71/story-nhmCHU3nNfu5VCh2j1sYiM.html | title=Artist Yusuf Arakkal passes away at 71 | date=4 October 2016 | newspaper=Hindustan Times | accessdate=31 January 2019 }}</ref><ref>http://www.yarakkal.com/bio.htm</ref><ref>https://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/noted-kerala-artist-yusuf-arakkal-dies-at-71/</ref>\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2016|10|04|1945}}<ref name=\"R1\"/>\n| death_place   = Bangalore, Karnataka\n| nationality   = Indian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Painting\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| spouse        = Sara<ref name=\"R2\">https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Yusuf-Arakkal-renowned-artist-passes-away-at-71/articleshow/54686982.cms</ref>\n| children      = Shibu (Son)<ref name=\"R2\"/>\n| website       = {{url|http://www.yarakkal.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Yusuf Arakkal''' (1945 \u2013 4 October 2016) was a [[Malayali]] painter. \n\n==Life==\n\nArakkal was born in Chavakkad, Kerala. Both his parents died when he was young. Leaving the comforts of his house behind, he left for [[Bangalore]], lonely but with a passion to become a painter. The hardships that he faced at Bangalore honed the artist in him and sharpened his sensibility.  He took a diploma in painting from ''[[Karnataka Chitrakala Parishat]]'' (KCP), Bangalore and later specialized in graphic print making from National Academy community studios, Garhi, [[Delhi]].{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}\n\nArakkal  received the prestigious ''Lorenzo De Medici Gold Medal'', at Florence Internazionale Biennale, in [[Florence]], [[Italy]] for his work ''Bacon\u2019s Man with the Child and Priest''. The artist produced a large collection of miscellaneous works consisting of drawings, paintings, sculptures, murals, paper works, prints and writing.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}} [https://www.firstpost.com/living/how-artist-yusuf-arakkal-who-passed-away-on-4-october-shaped-the-art-scene-in-bengaluru-3034316.html]\n\nHe won several other awards including ''Karnataka Lalithkala Academy'' award in 1979 and 1981, a national award in 1983, a special award at the third Asian Art Biennale Dhaka, Bangladesh in 1986 and the ''Karnataka Lalithkala Academy'' honor in 1989.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}\n\nArakkal's paintings are singularly expressionistic in style.  In them one could trace the artist's \"deep concern for man and society. Set against a dark, oppressive background are the faceless figures of ordinary people expressing brooding loneliness and despair brought on by a society obsessively drawn towards material success where ordinary people have no place\".He has done many works in different media, canvases, sculptures with emphasis on tiger conservation.<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/arts/art/article1996846.ece</ref>\n\nArakkal died in Bangalore on 4 October 2016 at the age of 70.<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/bengalurubased-artist-yusuf-arakkal-passes-away/article9183655.ece</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\nHe has conducted many exhibitions, both solo and group shows, internationally besides more than thirty national shows. His international shows are listed below.<ref>[http://www.onlinebangalore.com/life/art/yusuf.html Artist Profile: Yusuf Arakkal] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060221041947/http://www.onlinebangalore.com/life/art/yusuf.html |date=21 February 2006 }}, Online Bangalore.  Retrieved 26 October 2007.</ref>\n\n==Solo international shows==\n*1992 -\tRelays De Monts - Siux, Limousin, France.\n*1993 -\tGallerie Taormina Del Arte - Le Hwre, France.\n*1994 -\tSrijana Contemporary Art Gallery - Kathmandu, Nepal.\n*1994 -\tArt Forum Gallery, Singapore.\n*1996 -\tWallace Gallery, Chelsea, New York.\n*1996 -\tAir Gallery, Dower Street, London.\n\n==Group International shows==\n*1971 -\tIndian Artists at Belarus and Moscow.\n*1985 -\tThirty contemporary Indian Artists at Habana, Cuba.\n*1985 -\tContemporary Indian Art show at the National Museum Mexico City, Mexico.\n*1985 -\tSecond Asian Art show, Fukuoka, Japan.\n*1985 -\tIndian Printmaking, Festival of India, USA.\n*1986 -\tSixth biennale de beau Art, Beaumount, France.\n*1986 -\tThird Asian Art Biennale, Dhaka, Bangladesh.\n*1986 -\tInaugural exhibition of the National Museum of Modern Art, Seol, Korea.\n*1986 -\tSixth International Triennale, New Delhi, India.\n*1987 -\tNinth International Biennale de S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil.\n*1993 -\tNine Indian Artists CCA Gallery, New York.\n*1994 -\tIndian printmaking show, Maltwood Art Museum & Gallery Victoria, British Columbia.\n*1994 -\tIndian Contemporary Art Show, Gallery Maya, Hong Kong\n*1995 -\tHeads and faces - an exhibition by Gallery Maya, Visual Art Centre, Hong Kong.\n*1995 -\t'Save the children' auction by Sothebys, Bombay.\n*1996 -\tIndian Contemporary Art show, Nagai Garo, Tokyo, Japan\n*1996 -\t32 Contemporary Indian artists - exhibition and auction by Christies, London.\n*1996 -\tWomen in Indian Art, by The Gallery, Visual Art Centre, Hong Kong.\n*1997 -\tAuction of Indian Contemporary Art by Christies, London.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.saffronart.com/artists/yusuf-arakkal \"Yusuf Arakkal Profile,Interview and Artworks\"]\n*[http://www.yarakkal.com Yusuf Arakkal's official site]\n\n{{Painters from Kerala}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arakkal, Yusuf}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Malayali people]]\n[[Category:Painters from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Artists from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:People from Kozhikode district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Refimprove|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Yusuf Arakkal\n| image         = YusufArakkalPic.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Yusuf Arakkal\n| birth_date    = 1945\n| birth_place   = Chavakkad, Thrissur, Kerala<ref name=\"R1\">{{cite news | url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/art-and-culture/artist-yusuf-arakkal-passes-away-at-71/story-nhmCHU3nNfu5VCh2j1sYiM.html | title=Artist Yusuf Arakkal passes away at 71 | date=4 October 2016 | newspaper=Hindustan Times | accessdate=31 January 2019 }}</ref><ref>http://www.yarakkal.com/bio.htm</ref><ref>https://indianexpress.com/article/lifestyle/art-and-culture/noted-kerala-artist-yusuf-arakkal-dies-at-71/</ref>\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2016|10|04|1945}}<ref name=\"R1\"/>\n| death_place   = Bangalore, Karnataka\n| nationality   = Indian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Painting\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| spouse        = Sara<ref name=\"R2\">https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Yusuf-Arakkal-renowned-artist-passes-away-at-71/articleshow/54686982.cms</ref>\n| children      = Shibu (Son)<ref name=\"R2\"/>\n| website       = {{url|http://www.yarakkal.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Yusuf Arakkal''' (1945 \u2013 4 October 2016) was a [[Malayali]] painter. \n\n==Life==\n\nArakkal was born in Chavakkad, Kerala. Both his parents died when he was young. Leaving the comforts of his house behind, he left for [[Bangalore]], lonely but with a passion to become a painter. The hardships that he faced at Bangalore honed the artist in him and sharpened his sensibility.  He took a diploma in painting from ''[[Karnataka Chitrakala Parishat]]'' (KCP), Bangalore and later specialized in graphic print making from National Academy community studios, Garhi, [[Delhi]].{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}\n\nArakkal  received the prestigious ''Lorenzo De Medici Gold Medal'', at Florence Internazionale Biennale, in [[Florence]], [[Italy]] for his work ''Bacon\u2019s Man with the Child and Priest''. The artist produced a large collection of miscellaneous works consisting of drawings, paintings, sculptures, murals, paper works, prints and writing.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}\n\nHe won several other awards including ''Karnataka Lalithkala Academy'' award in 1979 and 1981, a national award in 1983, a special award at the third Asian Art Biennale Dhaka, Bangladesh in 1986 and the ''Karnataka Lalithkala Academy'' honor in 1989.{{Citation needed|date= April 2018}}\n\nArakkal's paintings are singularly expressionistic in style.  In them one could trace the artist's \"deep concern for man and society. Set against a dark, oppressive background are the faceless figures of ordinary people expressing brooding loneliness and despair brought on by a society obsessively drawn towards material success where ordinary people have no place\".He has done many works in different media, canvases, sculptures with emphasis on tiger conservation.<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/arts/art/article1996846.ece</ref>\n\nArakkal died in Bangalore on 4 October 2016 at the age of 70.<ref>http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/bengalurubased-artist-yusuf-arakkal-passes-away/article9183655.ece</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\nHe has conducted many exhibitions, both solo and group shows, internationally besides more than thirty national shows. His international shows are listed below.<ref>[http://www.onlinebangalore.com/life/art/yusuf.html Artist Profile: Yusuf Arakkal] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060221041947/http://www.onlinebangalore.com/life/art/yusuf.html |date=21 February 2006 }}, Online Bangalore.  Retrieved 26 October 2007.</ref>\n\n==Solo international shows==\n*1992 -\tRelays De Monts - Siux, Limousin, France.\n*1993 -\tGallerie Taormina Del Arte - Le Hwre, France.\n*1994 -\tSrijana Contemporary Art Gallery - Kathmandu, Nepal.\n*1994 -\tArt Forum Gallery, Singapore.\n*1996 -\tWallace Gallery, Chelsea, New York.\n*1996 -\tAir Gallery, Dower Street, London.\n\n==Group International shows==\n*1971 -\tIndian Artists at Belarus and Moscow.\n*1985 -\tThirty contemporary Indian Artists at Habana, Cuba.\n*1985 -\tContemporary Indian Art show at the National Museum Mexico City, Mexico.\n*1985 -\tSecond Asian Art show, Fukuoka, Japan.\n*1985 -\tIndian Printmaking, Festival of India, USA.\n*1986 -\tSixth biennale de beau Art, Beaumount, France.\n*1986 -\tThird Asian Art Biennale, Dhaka, Bangladesh.\n*1986 -\tInaugural exhibition of the National Museum of Modern Art, Seol, Korea.\n*1986 -\tSixth International Triennale, New Delhi, India.\n*1987 -\tNinth International Biennale de S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil.\n*1993 -\tNine Indian Artists CCA Gallery, New York.\n*1994 -\tIndian printmaking show, Maltwood Art Museum & Gallery Victoria, British Columbia.\n*1994 -\tIndian Contemporary Art Show, Gallery Maya, Hong Kong\n*1995 -\tHeads and faces - an exhibition by Gallery Maya, Visual Art Centre, Hong Kong.\n*1995 -\t'Save the children' auction by Sothebys, Bombay.\n*1996 -\tIndian Contemporary Art show, Nagai Garo, Tokyo, Japan\n*1996 -\t32 Contemporary Indian artists - exhibition and auction by Christies, London.\n*1996 -\tWomen in Indian Art, by The Gallery, Visual Art Centre, Hong Kong.\n*1997 -\tAuction of Indian Contemporary Art by Christies, London.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.saffronart.com/artists/yusuf-arakkal \"Yusuf Arakkal Profile,Interview and Artworks\"]\n*[http://www.yarakkal.com Yusuf Arakkal's official site]\n\n{{Painters from Kerala}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arakkal, Yusuf}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Malayali people]]\n[[Category:Painters from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Artists 